I"<p>Strong emotions experienced during an event often result in a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/recent-memories-are-malleable">more robust memory representation</a> being <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/fleeting-note-persisting-resembles-memory-consolidation">consolidated</a>. This is a prime example of how <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/triune-brain-model-classifies-brain-regions-through-evolutionary-lens">more “primitive” brain regions influence high-level cognition</a>. However, how could this be <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/optic-flow-modulates-autonomic-arousal">exapted</a> for <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/concept-learning-is-few-shot-scaffolding-supported-by-working-memory">concept learning</a> or <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/skill-acquisition-spans-cognitive-associative-autonomous-stages">skill acquisition</a>? How could user affect be <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/breathwork-modulates-autonomic-arousal">regulated</a>?</p>
